intent: >
  Wire HttpChecker into a Solid Queue background job that persists a
  CheckResult and transitions Site.status atomically. The 2xx/3xx → up,
  everything-else → down policy lands in this slice — where it belongs,
  not in the HTTP layer.

slice: 4/8
kind: feature
behavior_change: additive

reversibility: reversible
# New code only, no schema, no external state. `git revert` cleanly undoes.

scope:
  declared:
    - app/jobs/perform_check_job.rb
    - spec/jobs/perform_check_job_spec.rb
  actual:
    - app/jobs/perform_check_job.rb
    - spec/jobs/perform_check_job_spec.rb
  drift: []

proof:
  tests_run: bin/dc bundle exec rspec
  result: green
  failing: 0

tests:
  needed: "yes"
  added:
    - spec/jobs/perform_check_job_spec.rb

lint:
  run: bin/dc bundle exec rubocop app/jobs/perform_check_job.rb spec/jobs/perform_check_job_spec.rb
  result: clean
  count: 0

assumptions:
  - "perform takes site_id (integer), not a Site record. Solid Queue serializes the smaller payload and retries always re-fetch a fresh row."
  - "Up/down policy: 2xx and 3xx → up, 4xx and 5xx → down, transport error → down. 4xx is the most arguable bucket — chose 'down' because a 404 on the URL you're monitoring means the page is gone, which IS a downtime event for an uptime monitor. Easy to revisit per-site if the MVP shows it to be wrong."
  - "Persistence + status update are wrapped in a Site#transaction so a failed status update rolls back the CheckResult, never leaving an orphan check row."
  - "CheckResult creation goes through the foreign key (`CheckResult.create!(site: ..)`) rather than through `site.check_results.create!`, so `has_many :check_results` on Site stays deferred until a *reader* needs it (slice 6 or 7). This is consistent with slice 2's policy."
  - "HttpChecker is contractually responsible for not raising — its public API rescues Faraday::Error and URI::InvalidURIError. If something else does escape, the job lets it bubble up to Solid Queue's retry logic rather than swallowing it."

deviations_from_plan: >
  Plan said this slice should "enqueue DowntimeAlertJob on a up→down
  flip." There is no DowntimeAlertJob (slice 5's deliverable is
  DowntimeAlertMailer, not a job). Splitting the alert plumbing across
  two slices would mean wiring a stub in slice 4 that gets replaced one
  commit later — pure ceremony. Slice 5 will add the mailer AND the
  flip-detection hook in PerformCheckJob in one shippable unit. Plan
  has been updated.

trade_offs: >
  Considered moving derive_status onto HttpChecker::Result as `up?`,
  which would push the policy onto the value object. Rejected because
  it tangles HTTP truth (the Result's job) with product policy (the
  job's job). Keeping them apart means we can change "what counts as
  down" without touching fetch code.

self_review:
  consistency: >
    First background job in the repo. Sets the pattern: `perform`
    takes a primary key, side effects wrap in a transaction, the
    actual work delegates to private helper methods. Future jobs
    should match this shape or consciously diverge.
  metz: >
    `record_check` is 7 physical lines because CheckResult.create!
    has 5 keyword args. Same edge-case violation as HttpChecker's
    success_result/error_result (slice 3) — accepted because the
    alternatives are worse (positional create! loses readability,
    inlined into perform makes that method 12+ lines).
  mocking: >
    Canonical "mock at the seam" example. HttpChecker is mocked
    because we own it (not webmock-stubbing Net::HTTP this time).
    The job spec controls what HttpChecker returns and asserts the
    job's resulting side effects. Slice 3's spec covers the actual
    HTTP behavior — no need to re-verify here.
  error_paths: >
    Concurrent runs of PerformCheckJob for the same Site are not
    locked. Both will create CheckResults (independent rows, no
    corruption) and both will update Site.status (last write wins).
    For the MVP this is acceptable: slice 6's scheduler should not
    enqueue overlapping runs because it filters by last_checked_at.
    If we ever see a real race, an advisory lock on Site.id at the
    top of perform is the natural fix. Flagged here so the reviewer
    isn't surprised by the missing lock.
  feature_envy: >
    derive_status arguably belongs on HttpChecker::Result (as `up?`).
    Deliberate kept on the job: HTTP truth (Result's responsibility)
    should not be tangled with product policy (the job's
    responsibility). Cross-layer cohesion beats single-object
    convenience here.
  api: >
    New public API: PerformCheckJob.perform_now(site_id) and
    .perform_later(site_id). Slice 6's scheduler will be the only
    caller. The integer-ID-only signature is a soft semver boundary
    — changing it to take a Site record or extra args would break
    the scheduler.

confidence: high

reviewer_attention:
  - app/jobs/perform_check_job.rb:31-35  # the up/down policy — the most product-shaped decision in the slice
  - app/jobs/perform_check_job.rb:7-10   # the transaction wrapper — atomicity guarantee
